         <abstract>
            <p>In this paper we test for the existence of systematic differences in the premiums paid to acquired firm shareholders across merger types and payment methods. Pure conglomerate mergers are found to be associated with slightly larger, although not significantly larger, cumulative average residuals for the shareholders of the acquired firms. Significant differences do appear to exist across payment methods, with cash acquisitions involving substantially higher abnormal returns. We attribute the difference principally to a tax effect and to regulatory differences favoring cash acquisitions.</p>
         </abstract>
